<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWS, TIPS & BARGAINS; GRAVE IS HIGH ON LIST OF MUST-SEES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The movie "Schindler's List" has turned the grave of Oskar Schindler in the 
Latin Cemetery just outside the Old City of Jerusalem, into a tourist 
attraction, according to the Israel Ministry of Tourism. 
</P>
<P>
 Although no one's officially counting, there's been a "tremendous upsurge" in 
visitors to the grave, a spokesperson said. "Before the film, hardly anyone 
asked about it." The guard now opens the gate from 9 a.m. to noon daily at the 
Catholic cemetery, where the German businessman who saved 1,200 Jews from the 
Holocaust was buried 20 years ago. 
</P>
