<HEADLINE>
<P>
HOW THE DOLLAR HAS FARED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The U.S. dollar has fallen roughly a third in value against the Japanese yen 
since 1989 and about 12% against the German mark since 1988. Yet, the greenback 
has also held fairly steady against the British pound in recent years and 
appreciated 19% against the Canadian dollar. The dollar in these currencies: 
</P>
<P>
 Japanese Yen: Friday: 99.95 
</P>
<P>
 German Marks: Friday: 1.583 
</P>
<P>
 British Pounds: Friday: 0.6481 
</P>
<P>
 Canadian Dollars: Friday: 1.387 
</P>
<P>
 Source: International Monetary Fund; TradeLine 
</P>
<P>
 Note: Figures are year-end closes, except latest 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA073194-0338 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 065857 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
July 31, 1994, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
